    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "### Problem\n\n`src/nvim/globals.h` declares ~283 `EXTERN` symbols across 809 lines and is included by ~140 translation units. Every C file that includes it pulls in the entire shared mutable namespace of the editor: search state, ex-command state, normal-mode state, regexp state, message state, and more — all reachable from anywhere, with no static qualifiers (by definition).\n\nConcrete consequences:\n\n- **Subsystems are not independently reasonable.** `search.c`, `ex_docmd.c`, `normal.c`, and `regexp*.c` reach into shared globals rather than receiving their state via parameters, so their preconditions and invariants aren't expressible at the function signature level.\n- **Unit-testing those modules is impractical.** Today only functional tests (full `nvim` process, Lua-driven) exercise this code; there is no seam to instantiate a subsystem in isolation with a known state.\n- **Reentrancy / threading are foreclosed.** Anything that one day wants to run a regexp match, a search, or an ex-command off the main thread (e.g. background indexing, per-buffer parsers) hits the global-state wall.\n- **C → Lua migration is incomplete.** As more user-visible behavior moves to Lua, the C core that remains should be a set of well-bounded services with explicit inputs/outputs — not a shared bag of globals. The current shape makes it harder to expose clean APIs to the Lua layer.\n\nRelated prior art: Vim 9 has begun similar bounding work; other editors (Helix, Zed) are built around explicit-context designs from day one.\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nIncremental, opt-in migration — **not** a flag-day rewrite (which would permanently fork from Vim and break upstream patch-port).",
