            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": ">  Subsystems are not independently reasonable\n\nsomewhat related, we have a `iwyu` target: https://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/33ea63011ca3c78b2a453dc6669ba5bf39147d9a/Makefile#L157-L160\n\n\n\n> **Unit-testing those modules is impractical.** Today only functional tests (full `nvim` process, Lua-driven) exercise this code; there is no seam to instantiate a subsystem in isolation with a known state.\n\nThat's kind of a fake problem. The main reason \"unit tests\" are usually wanted is because the whole system is slow. Whereas `nvim` starts in 30ms.\n\nIf you could spin up an entire AWS cloud in 1 second, you would not \"unit test\" it. You would test the entire system. Because end-to-end tests are vastly superior, except when they are *slow*.\n\nMeanwhile, we actually do have [unit-tests](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/tree/33ea63011ca3c78b2a453dc6669ba5bf39147d9a/test/unit), unlike Vim.\n\n> C → Lua migration is incomplete. As more user-visible behavior moves to Lua, the C core that remains should be a set of well-bounded services with explicit inputs/outputs — not a shared bag of globals\n\nAs we move code to Lua, that becomes more feasible. Whereas your proposal swaps the order.\n\n> Related prior art: Vim 9 has begun similar bounding work\n\nWhere? We will merge those patches. But I doubt that's actually true.",
